===Etymology===
{{etyl|la|en}} {{term|trans-|lang=la}} + {{term|vestite|lang=la}}, form of {{term|vestiō||I clothe, I dress|lang=la}} (as in English {{term|vestment|lang=en}}, {{term|vest|lang=en}}). Literally, a "cross-dresser".

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A person who sometimes wears [[clothes]] traditionally worn by and associated with the opposite [[sex]]; typically a male who cross-dresses occasionally by habit or compulsion.

====Usage notes====
This term is relatively formal (Latinate); {{term|cross-dresser|lang=en}} is more casual, but whereas the verb {{term|cross-dress|lang=en}} is common, the verb {{term|transvest|lang=en}} is quite rare.

''Transvestite'' should not be confused with ''[[transgender]]'' or {{term|transsexual||person who lives as a member of a sex different from their birth sex}}. Transvestites generally have less or no desire to change their sex; they simply enjoy being able to cross-dress from time to time.

The term should also not be confused with {{term|drag queen||male who wears women’s clothing for public performance}}; that term is specifically for performers.

